2. ABSTRACT
================================================================================
This project presents a comprehensive machine learning-powered web application for 
heart disease prediction using the Cleveland Heart Disease dataset from the UCI 
Machine Learning Repository. The system implements four ML algorithms (Random 
Forest, Logistic Regression, Support Vector Machine, Decision Tree) with 
comparative analysis using 10-fold cross-validation.

Built using Python and Streamlit, the application provides an intuitive interface 
for healthcare professionals to input 13 medical features and receive risk 
assessments with probability scores. The project introduces mean imputation as a 
superior alternative to row deletion for handling missing values, preserving 100% 
of data (303 records).

Key Features:
- 87% accuracy with Random Forest classifier
- Mean imputation preserving dataset integrity (303→303 records)
- Explainable AI with feature importance visualization
- Batch prediction for multiple patients
- PDF/HTML report generation
- Role-based authentication (Admin/Doctor)
- Interactive analytics dashboard
- 10-fold cross-validation for robust evaluation

The system demonstrates significant improvement over traditional preprocessing 
methods, increasing accuracy by 4% through better data utilization. The web 
interface is designed for clinical integration with professional UI/UX.

================================================================================
3. INTRODUCTION
================================================================================

3.1 PROBLEM STATEMENT
Heart disease remains the leading cause of mortality worldwide, accounting for 
17.9 million deaths annually according to the World Health Organization (WHO). 
Early detection and intervention are critical for improving patient outcomes. 
However, traditional diagnostic methods can be time-consuming and may not 
effectively utilize the wealth of available patient data.

3.2 RESEARCH GAP
While numerous machine learning studies exist for heart disease prediction, 
several gaps remain:
- Many systems use row deletion (dropna()) losing valuable medical data
- "Black box" models without explainability hinder clinical adoption
- Lack of user-friendly interfaces for healthcare professionals
- Limited batch processing capabilities for screening programs
- Insufficient documentation of preprocessing innovations

3.3 OBJECTIVES
Primary Objectives:
1. Develop accurate ML models for heart disease prediction (Target: >85% accuracy)
2. Implement proper missing value handling using mean imputation
3. Create an intuitive web interface with Streamlit
4. Provide model explainability through feature importance
5. Enable batch processing for clinical workflows

Secondary Objectives:
1. Compare multiple ML algorithms with cross-validation
2. Generate downloadable PDF/HTML reports
3. Implement role-based authentication
4. Create comprehensive documentation (teaching notebook)
5. Design professional UI with modern aesthetics

