4. LITERATURE REVIEW
================================================================================

4.1 DATASET: CLEVELAND HEART DISEASE (UCI)
Source: UCI Machine Learning Repository
Dataset: Heart Disease Dataset (Cleveland subset)
URL: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/heart+disease

Original Samples: 303
After Processing: 303 (mean imputation preserves all records)
Features: 13 medical attributes + 1 target variable
Class Distribution: 164 no-disease, 139 heart disease cases

Target Binarization (5→2 Classes):
- Original UCI: 0=No disease, 1-4=Disease severity (5 classes)
- Our Dataset: 0=No disease, 1=Disease (binary, already preprocessed)
- Reason: 303 samples too small for 5-class classification
- Result: Better accuracy (87% vs. ~70% for multi-class)

4.2 RELATED WORK
Key Studies:
1. Yan et al. (2020) - "Heart Disease Prediction Using Machine Learning"
   - Achieved 88.9% accuracy using ensemble methods
   - Used Cleveland dataset with 303 records
   - Emphasized feature selection importance

2. Amin et al. (2019) - "Heart Disease Prediction Using ML Techniques"
   - Compared 5 ML algorithms
   - Best performance: Random Forest (85.7%)
   - Highlighted preprocessing significance

3. Most existing studies use row deletion (dropna()) for missing values
   - This approach loses data (varies by subset)
   - Our innovation: Mean imputation preserves all records

4.3 THEORETICAL BACKGROUND

4.3.1 Supervised Learning Algorithms

A. LOGISTIC REGRESSION (83% Accuracy)
Type: Linear model for binary classification
Formula: P(y=1) = 1/(1 + e^(-z))
         where z = β₀ + β₁x₁ + β₂x₂ + ... + β₁₃x₁₃
- β₀ = intercept term
- β₁...β₁₃ = learned weights
- x₁...x₁₃ = input features

Strengths: Simple, fast, probabilistic output
Weaknesses: Assumes linear decision boundary

B. RANDOM FOREST (87% Accuracy - BEST MODEL)
Type: Ensemble of decision trees using bagging
Mechanism: 
- Creates N=100 decision trees (estimators)
- Each tree trained on bootstrap sample
- Majority vote for classification
- Feature randomness: √p features per split

Split Criterion (Gini Impurity):
Gini = 1 - Σ(pᵢ)² for i=1 to C classes
where pᵢ = proportion of class i in node

Strengths: Reduces overfitting, feature importance, robust
Weaknesses: Less interpretable than single tree

C. SUPPORT VECTOR MACHINE (85% Accuracy)
Type: Kernel-based classification algorithm
Mechanism: Find optimal hyperplane maximizing margin
Hyperplane: w·x + b = 0
where w = weight vector, b = bias term

RBF Kernel: K(x,y) = exp(-γ||x-y||²)
where γ = 1/(2σ²), controls kernel width

Strengths: Works well with high-dimensional data
Weaknesses: Sensitive to hyperparameters, needs feature scaling

D. DECISION TREE (80% Accuracy)
Type: Tree-based model using recursive binary partitioning
Mechanism: Split data at each node to maximize information gain
Split Criteria:
- Gini: G = 1 - Σ(pᵢ)²
- Entropy: H = -Σpᵢ × log₂(pᵢ)
- Information Gain = H(parent) - Σ(wᵢ × H(childᵢ))

Strengths: Highly interpretable (tree structure)
Weaknesses: Prone to overfitting

4.3.2 Model Evaluation Metrics

A. ACCURACY = (TP + TN) / (TP + TN + FP + FN)
   Overall correctness of predictions

B. PRECISION = TP / (TP + FP)
   Of predicted "Disease", how many are correct?
   (Minimize false alarms)

C. RECALL/SENSITIVITY = TP / (TP + FN)
   Of actual "Disease", how many caught?
   (Minimize missed diagnoses - CRITICAL for medical)

D. F1-SCORE = 2 × (Precision × Recall) / (Precision + Recall)
   Harmonic mean of precision and recall

E. ROC CURVE (Receiver Operating Characteristic)
   Plot of True Positive Rate vs. False Positive Rate
   TPR = Recall = TP / (TP + FN)
   FPR = FP / (FP + TN)

F. AUC (Area Under ROC Curve)
   0.5 = random classifier
   1.0 = perfect classifier
   Our Result: 0.95 (excellent)

4.3.3 Cross-Validation
k-fold CV: Split data into k subsets (folds)
- Train on k-1 folds, test on 1 fold
- Repeat k times, each fold used once as test
- Final score = average of k scores

Formula: CV_score = (1/k) × Σ Accuracyᵢ for i=1 to k

Why 10-fold?
- More reliable than 5-fold for small datasets
- Better utilizes limited data (303 samples)
- Provides confidence intervals
- Standard in medical ML literature

4.3.4 Missing Value Handling

Dataset Missing Values:
- ca (Major Vessels): 4 missing (NaN)
- thal (Thalassemia): 2 missing (NaN)
- All other columns: 0 missing
- Total: 6 missing values out of 4,242 cells

Traditional Method (NOT USED):
df = df.dropna()  # Would remove 6 rows, leaving 297
Problem: Even small data loss reduces training samples

Our Solution (IMPLEMENTED):
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')
X_imputed = imputer.fit_transform(X)

Why Mean Imputation?
- Preserves 100% of records (303→303)
- Simple and fast
- Works well for numerical medical data
- No bias introduction for this dataset size

Comparison Table:
| Method | Rows Preserved | Accuracy | Complexity | Bias |
|--------|----------------|----------|------------|------|
| dropna() | 297/303 (98%) | ~86% | Low | Low |
| Mean Imputation | 303/303 (100%) | 87% | Low | Low |
| KNN Imputation | 303/303 (100%) | ~87% | Medium | Very Low |
| MICE | 303/303 (100%) | ~88% | High | Lowest |

================================================================================
5. METHODOLOGY
================================================================================

5.1 DATA PREPROCESSING

5.1.1 Target Binarization (5→2 Classes)
Original UCI Cleveland dataset has 5 target values:
- 0 = No heart disease
- 1 = Mild heart disease
- 2 = Moderate heart disease
- 3 = Severe heart disease
- 4 = Critical heart disease

For binary classification (yes/no disease), we merge 1-4 into 1:
- 0 → 0 (No disease)
- 1,2,3,4 → 1 (Disease present)

Our dataset (heartt_cleveland_cleaned.csv) is already binarized:
- 0 = No disease (164 cases, 54%)
- 1 = Disease (139 cases, 46%)

Reason: 303 samples too small for 5-class → binary gives 87% accuracy

5.1.2 Dataset Features (13 Input Variables)
1. Age (29-77 years) - Numerical
2. Sex (Male=1, Female=0) - Binary categorical
3. cp (Chest Pain Type) - Ordinal (1=Typical, 2=Atypical, 3=Non-anginal, 4=Asymptomatic)
4. trestbps (Resting Blood Pressure) - Numerical (94-200 mmHg)
5. chol (Serum Cholesterol) - Numerical (126-564 mg/dl)
6. fbs (Fasting Blood Sugar >120 mg/dl) - Binary (0=No, 1=Yes)
7. restecg (Resting ECG Results) - Ordinal (0=Normal, 1=ST-T abnormality, 2=LV hypertrophy)
8. thalach (Max Heart Rate) - Numerical (71-202 bpm)
9. exang (Exercise Induced Angina) - Binary (0=No, 1=Yes)
10. oldpeak (ST Depression) - Numerical (0-6.2 mm)
11. slope (Slope of Peak Exercise ST) - Ordinal (1=Up, 2=Flat, 3=Down)
12. ca (Number of Major Vessels) - Ordinal (0-3, 4 missing values)
13. thal (Thalassemia) - Ordinal (3=Normal, 6=Fixed Defect, 7=Reversible Defect, 2 missing)

Target Variable:
- 0 = No Heart Disease (164 cases, 54%)
- 1 = Heart Disease (139 cases, 46%)

5.1.3 Data Cleaning Steps
Step 1: Load dataset
df = pd.read_csv('data/heartt_cleveland_cleaned.csv')
Result: 303 × 14 (no invalid entries like thal=0)

Step 2: Handle missing values with mean imputation
imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')
X_imputed = pd.DataFrame(
    imputer.fit_transform(X), 
    columns=X.columns
)
Result: 303 → 303 rows (100% preserved!)

Step 3: Feature scaling (Standardization)
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_imputed)
Formula: z = (x - μ) / σ
Result: Zero mean, unit variance for all features

Why Scale?
- Critical for distance-based algorithms (SVM, KNN)
- Prevents features with larger ranges from dominating
- Example: Cholesterol (126-564) vs. Sex (0-1)

5.2 MODEL DEVELOPMENT

5.2.1 Data Split
- Training set: 80% (303 × 0.8 = 242 samples)
- Test set: 20% (303 × 0.2 = 61 samples)
- Stratified split: Preserves class distribution (54% no-disease, 46% disease)

5.2.2 Models Configured
1. Random Forest:
   - n_estimators=100 (number of trees)
   - random_state=42 (reproducibility)
   - max_depth=None (grow until pure)

2. Logistic Regression:
   - max_iter=1000 (convergence)
   - random_state=42
   - solver='lbfgs' (default)

3. Support Vector Machine:
   - kernel='rbf' (Radial Basis Function)
   - probability=True (for predict_proba)
   - random_state=42
   - C=1.0 (regularization)

4. Decision Tree:
   - max_depth=10 (prevent overfitting)
   - random_state=42
   - criterion='gini'

5.2.3 Training Process
1. Fit imputer on training set ONLY
2. Fit scaler on training set ONLY
3. Transform training data
4. Train all 4 models
5. 10-fold cross-validation on training data
6. Select best model (highest CV accuracy)
7. Evaluate on test set

5.2.4 Model Persistence
Save all required objects:
joblib.dump(best_model, 'models/model.pkl')
joblib.dump(scaler, 'models/scaler.pkl')
joblib.dump(imputer, 'models/imputer.pkl')  # NEW - Critical!
joblib.dump(X.columns.tolist(), 'models/feature_names.pkl')

5.3 SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE

Frontend (Streamlit Web App - app.py):
- Welcome Page: Background image, "Login to System" button
- Login System: Admin/Doctor roles, session management
- Prediction Tab: 13-feature input form, real-time prediction
- Compare Tab: Side-by-side model performance comparison
- Stats Tab: Analytics dashboard with history
- Features Tab: Feature importance visualization (top 5)
- Analysis Tab: ROC curve, Confusion Matrix, Correlation Heatmap
- History Tab: Session-based prediction history, CSV export
- Batch Tab: CSV upload for bulk predictions (NEW)
- Reports: HTML/PDF download after each prediction

Backend (Python - src/):
- train_model.py: Training with mean imputation
- predictor.py: Prediction class loading imputer/scaler/model
- analyze.py: Data analysis and visualization tools

Persistence Layer:
- Joblib: Model, scaler, imputer serialization
- JSON: User credentials (users.json)
- Session State: Prediction history (no database)

