================================================================================
APPENDIX B: DEFENSE Q&A (EXPECTED QUESTIONS)
================================================================================

Q1: "Why did you choose mean imputation over dropping rows?"
A: "Our dataset has only 6 missing values (4 in ca, 2 in thal). Using dropna() 
    would lose 6 rows (2% data). Mean imputation preserves all 303 records, 
    contributing to our 87% accuracy."

Q2: "Why 10-fold cross-validation instead of 5-fold?"
A: "With only 303 samples, 10-fold provides more reliable estimates by using 
    29 samples per test fold. It's standard in medical ML literature and 
    provides confidence intervals for model performance."

Q3: "Why Random Forest over other models?"
A: "Random Forest achieved highest accuracy (87%) and CV score. Its ensemble 
    nature reduces overfitting, provides built-in feature importance, and 
    handles numerical/categorical data well without extensive preprocessing."

Q4: "How does feature importance help doctors?"
A: "It moves from 'black box' to 'glass box' AI. Doctors can see that 
    'cholesterol level contributed 23% to this prediction,' building trust 
    and aiding clinical decision-making."

Q5: "Why did you remove the database?"
A: "We simplified for academic demonstration. The focus is on ML preprocessing 
    and model comparison. Database integration is standard but not core to ML 
    learning objectives. Streamlit session state works for our educational purpose."

Q6: "How do you handle class imbalance?"
A: "The dataset is relatively balanced (54% no-disease, 46% disease). If 
    imbalance were severe (<30% minority class), we would use SMOTE, ADASYN, 
    or adjust class weights in algorithms."

Q7: "Can this replace a doctor's diagnosis?"
A: "ABSOLUTELY NOT. This is a decision support tool ONLY. Final diagnosis 
    must come from qualified medical professionals. The system aids, not replaces."

Q8: "Why use Streamlit instead of Flask/Django?"
A: "Streamlit is purpose-built for ML demos with minimal code. It provides 
    interactive widgets, real-time updates, and clean UI out-of-the-box. 
    Flask/Django would require extensive frontend work."

Q9: "What is the clinical workflow integration?"
A: "Doctors login, enter patient data, get prediction + feature importance, 
    download HTML report for records, and can process batches for screening 
    programs. No EHR integration yet (future work)."

Q10: "How do you ensure patient data privacy?"
A: "No persistent database (session state only), no external API calls, 
     local deployment only. For production, would need HIPAA compliance, 
     encryption, audit logs, and secure cloud deployment."

Q11: "Why binary classification instead of multi-class (5 levels)?"
A: "With only 303 samples, 5-class classification would have too few samples 
     per class (some classes <20). Binary gives 87% accuracy vs. ~70% for 
     multi-class. Binary is also standard for clinical screening (yes/no)."

Q12: "How does the prediction work with 13 features?"
A: "Features go through: 1) Mean imputation (fill NaN), 2) Standard scaling 
     (normalize), 3) Random Forest (100 trees vote). Majority vote = 
     prediction, vote ratio = confidence %."

